{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> τρέφω</b>, <br /> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.52, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Doric dialect</i> <b>τράφω</b> (see. entry); <i>1st pers.</i> <i>singular</i> <i>optative</i> τρέφοιν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 903 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>future</i> θρέψω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “hymnus ad Venerem” 257, etc.: \">Refs</a>]<i>aorist 1</i> ἔθρεψα, <i>Epic dialect</i> θρέψα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.548: \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>aorist 2</i> ἔτρᾰφον (see. infr. B): <i>perfect</i> τέτροφα <i>intransitive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 23.237, (συν-) 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ ἱερῆς νούσου” 11; but _transitive_, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 186 (Lyric poetry); also τέτρᾰφα 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 12.25h. 5:\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] —<i>middle</i>, <i>future</i> θρέψομαι in <i>passive</i> sense, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “Genit.” 9, “Nat.Puer.” 23, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 7.49, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ἐθρεψάμην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 6.46, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 928 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], etc.:—<i>passive</i>, <i>future</i> τρᾰφήσομαι Ps.-[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 60.32, 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 8.41 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>], etc., but in early writers in <i>middle</i> form θρέψομαι (see. above): <i>aorist 1</i> ἐθρέφθην, <i>Epic dialect</i> θρέφθη [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 198 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], rare in Trag. and <i>Attic dialect</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 351, 600, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Politicus” 310a; ἐθράφθη “IG” 12(9).286 (Eretria, 6th c.BC): \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]<i>aorist 2</i> ἐτράφην [ᾰ] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus (sed see infr. B), 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 754 (Lyric poetry), 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 335 (Lyric poetry), etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>plural</i> ἔτραφεν, τράφεν, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.348, 1.251 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> τέθραμμαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ φύσιος ἀνθρώπου” 5, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Heraclidae” 578, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>2nd pers.</i> <i>plural</i> τέθραφθε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 625a (but συντέτραφθε\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] [assuming variant] in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 6.4.14)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>infinitive</i> τεθράφθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 525a, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 2.3.24 (in both with see l. τετρ-). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__I</b></Level2> <b>thicken</b> or <b>congeal</b> a liquid, γάλα θρέψαι <b>curdle</b> it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 9.246 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τρέφε (<i>imperfect</i>) πίονατυρόν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 25.106:\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>] —<i>passive</i>, with <i>perfect</i> <i>active</i> τέτροφα, <b>curdle, congeal,</b> γάλα τρεφόμενον τυρὸν ἐργάζεσθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “De Natura Animalium - Ar.Byzantine Epit.” 16.32; περὶ χροΐ τέτροφεν ἅλμη 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 23.237. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> usually, <b>cause to grow</b> or <b>increase, bring up, rear,</b> especially of children bred and brought up in a house, ὅ σ᾽ ἔτρεφε τυτθὸν ἐόντα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 8.283; ἥ μ᾽ ἔτεχ᾽, ἥ μ᾽ ἔθρεψε 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.131, compare 12.134; εὖ ἔτρεφεν ἠδ᾽ ἀτίταλλεν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 16.191, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 19.354; ἐγώ σ᾽ ἔθρεψα, σὺν δὲ γηράναι θέλω 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 908, compare “Supp.” 894; μέχρι ἥβης τ. 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.46; γεννᾶν καὶ τ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Politicus” 274a; τ. τε καὶ αὔξειν μέγαν [prev. author] “R.” 565c: with _accusative_ _cognate_, τ. τινὰ τροφήν τινα\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] <b>bring up</b> in a certain way, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.2; also τῶν πρώτων μαθημάτων, ἐν οἷς οἱ παλαιοὶ τοὺς παῖδας ἔτρεφον 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 16.691 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>middle</i>, <b>rear for oneself,</b> θρέψαιό τε φαίδιμον υἱόν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 19.368; αὐτὸν ἐθρέψαντο δράκοντες 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 6.46; τεκοῦσα τόνδ᾽ ὄφιν ἐθρεψάμην 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 928; οἱ γεννήσαντες καὶ θρεψάμενοι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 717c; τεκὼν ἀρετὴν καὶ θ. [prev. author] “Smp.” 212a; ἔτεκον μὲν ὑμᾶς πολεμίοις δ᾽ ἐθρεψάμην ὕβρισμα 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hercules Furens” 458 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, <b>to be reared, grow up,</b> ὅς μοι τηλύγετος τρέφεται θαλίῃ ἔνι πολλῇ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 9.143; τῇ ὁμοῦ ἐτρεφόμην 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 15.365; ἅμα τράφεν ἠδ᾽ ἐγένοντο 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.251, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; κάρτιστοι τράφεν ἀνδρῶν <b>grew up</b> the strongest men, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 266 \">Refs</a>]:—properly a boy was called τρεφόμενος only so long as he remained in the charge of the women, i. e. till his fifth year, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.136 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐξ ὅτου 'τράφην ἐγώ from the time when I <b>left the nursery,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 322 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but even of pre-natal growth, ἐν σκότοισινηδύος τεθραμμένη [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 665, compare “Th.” 754 (Lyric poetry):—generally, in Trag., τραφεὶς μητρὸς εὐγενοῦς ἄπο 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 1229 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὅπως πατρὸς δείξεις οἷος ἐξ οἵου τράφης[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 557; κρατίστου πατρὸς.. τραφείς [prev. author] “Ph.” 3: παῖδες μητέρων τεθραμμέναι\">Refs</a>] <b>true nurslings of</b> your mothers, implying a reproach for unmanliness (assuming variant), [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 792 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; μιᾶς τρέφει πρὸς νυκτός <b>art nursed</b> by night alone, i. e. art blind, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 374. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> of slaves, cattle, dogs and the like, <b>rear and keep</b> them, κύνας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 22.69, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.22, etc.; ἵππους 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.766 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; λέοντος ἶνιν (see. σίνις) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 717 (Lyric poetry); μῆλα [prev. author] “Eu.” 946 (Lyric poetry); ὄφιν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 226 (conjecture for στρέφουσι); ἰκτῖνα 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 628; ὄρτυγας 5th c.BC: Eupolis Comicus 214; ὄρνιθας 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 197c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οἱ τρέφοντες (i.e. τοὺς ἐλέφαντας) the <b>keepers,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 571b33; τ. παιδαγωγούς 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 1.187; also τ. γυναῖκα 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Aulidensis” 749 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τ. [ἑταίραν], [πόρνας], <b>keep</b>.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Antiphanes Comicus 2, 4th-3rd c.BC: Diphilus Comicus 87 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ὁ τρέφων one's <b>master,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC(?): Nicolaus Comicus 1.11, 36: _metaphorically_, αἰγιαλὸν ἔνδον τρέφει\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] <b>he keeps</b> a sea-beach in the house, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 110 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, <b>to be bred, reared,</b> δοῦλος οὐκ ὠνητός, ἀλλ᾽ οἴκοι τραφείς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1123 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐν τῇ σῇ οἰκίᾳ γέγονεν καὶ τέθραπται was born and <b>bred,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Meno” 85e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; Ἀγαθῖνον θρεμένον (i. e. τεθρεμμένον, ={θρεπτόν}, see at {θρεπτός} [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1) ἑαυτῶν “MAMA” 4.275 B (Dionysopolis, 2nd c.AD)\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; Νείκην τὴν θρεμένην μου [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work]276 A (Dionysopolis, 2nd c.AD). \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> <b>tend, cherish,</b> τὸν μὲν ἐγὼ φίλεόν τε καὶ ἔτρεφον, of Calypso, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.135, compare 7.256 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of plants, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 17.53; θρέψασα φυτὸν ὥς 18.57, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.175. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> of parts of the body, <b>let grow, cherish, foster,</b> χαίτην.. Σπερχειῷ τρέφε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.142; τῷ θεῷ [πλόκαμον] τ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Bacchae” 494; ὑπήνην ἄκουρον τ. 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 476 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τ. κόμην, ={κομᾶν}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.82; [τρίχες] πολλῷ ἐλαίῳ τραφεῖσαι 2nd-1st c.BC(?): Hero Mechanicus “Belopoeica” 112: also τά θ᾽ ὕεσσι τρέφει ἀλοιφήν\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] things which <b>put</b> fat <b>on</b> swine, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 13.410; τεθραμμένη εἰς πολυσαρκίαν 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.1.22. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.5</b></Level3> in Poets, of earth and sea, <b>breed, produce, teem with,</b> οὐδὲν ἀκιδνότερον γαῖα τ. ἀνθρώποιο [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 18.130; ἄγρια, τά τε τρέφει οὔρεσιν ὕλη 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.52; φάρμακα, ὅσα τρέφει εὐρεῖα χθών 11.741; ὅσ᾽ ἤπειρος.. τρέφει ἠδὲ θάλασσα 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 582; πολλὰ γᾶ τρέφει δεινά 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 585 (Lyric poetry), compare 128, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 1181; θάλασσα.. τρέφουσα πορφύρας ἰσάργυρον κηκῖδα 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 959 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὃν πόντος τ., i. e. the sailors, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “I.” 1.48 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: rare in Prose, ἀεί τι ἡ Αιβύη τρέφει καινόν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Generatione Animalium” 746b8. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.6</b></Level3> in Poets also, simply, <b>have within oneself, contain,</b> ὅ τι καὶ πόλις τέτροφεν ἄφιλον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 186 (Lyric poetry), compare “Tr.” 817 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τρέφειν τὴν γλῶσσαν ἡσυχαιτέραν <b>to keep</b> his tongue more quiet, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ant.” 1089; ἡ γλῶσσα τὸν θυμὸν δεινὸν τ. [prev. author] “Aj.” 1124; τἀληθὲς γὰρ ἰσχῦον τρέφω [prev. author] “OT” 356 (so in 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus, τ. ἰσχυρὸν τὸ ἐλεινόν “R.” 606b); τ. νόσον 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 795; ἐκ φόβου φόβον τ. [prev. author] “Tr.” 28; ἄταν [prev. author] “Aj.” 644 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οἵας λατρείας.. τρέφει what services.. <b>she has as her lot,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 503 \">Refs</a>]; ἐν ἐλπίσιν τρέφω.. ἥξειν I <b>cherish</b> hopes that.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ant.” 897 \">Refs</a>]; τὸν Καδμογενῆ τρέφει.. βιότου πολύπονον [πέλαγος] <b>is</b> his <b>daily lot,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Tr.” 117 (Lyric poetry, but Reiske's conjecture στρέφει is probably)\">Refs</a>]; πόνοι τρέφοντες βροτούς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 367 (Lyric poetry). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <b>maintain, support,</b> τ. ἀνδρὸς μόχθος ἡμένας ἔσω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 921, compare 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 9.106; τοῦ τρέφοντος Ἡλίου χθονὸς φύσιν 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 633; τ. τὸν πατέρα 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 1.13; τὴν οἰκίαν ὅλην 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 59.67; οὐ δίκαιον τρέφεσθαι ὑπὸ πατρὸς ὑὸν ἡβῶντα 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 568e; τὰ κτήνη χιλῷ ἐτρέφοντο 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 4.5.25 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; γάλακτι, τυρῷ, κρέασι τ., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Mem.” 4.3.10 \">Refs</a>]; σίτῳ, ὄψῳ, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Lac.” 1.3 \">Refs</a>]; <b>feed</b> a patient, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 15.503, 19.185\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; <b>provide the food for</b> an employee, σοῦ τρέφοντος αὐτόν, ἐμοῦ δὲ ἱματίζοντος αὐτόν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “BGU” 1647.14 (2nd c.AD)\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; also τ. ἀπό τινος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 313c, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 2.1.1; ἔκ τινος 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1479 (Lyric poetry), compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 372b. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.2</b></Level3> <b>maintain</b> an army or fleet, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 4.83, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 1.1.9 (_passive_)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τ. τὰς ναῦς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 8.44, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 1.5.5, 5.1.24 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τ. τὸ ναυτικὸν ἀπὸ τῶν νήσων[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 4.8.9; ἐκ τῶν κωμῶν τρέφεσθαι [prev. author] “An.” 7.4.11, etc. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.3</b></Level3> of land, <b>feed, maintain</b> one, τρέφει γὰρ οὗτος [ὁ ἀγρὸς].. με [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Philemo Comicus 98.2, compare 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus 63, 466, +others \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.4</b></Level3> of women, <b>feed</b> or <b>suckle</b> an infant, συνεξομοιοῦται τὰ τρεφόμενα ταῖς τρεφούσαις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Soranus Medicus 1.88; γυνὴ τρέφουσα [prev. work] 87 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; ἡ τρέφουσα, ={ἡ τροφός}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 6.44. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__III.5</b></Level3> of food, <b>nourish,</b> τὰ Ἡρακλεωτικὰ τρέφει οὐχ ὁμοίως τοῖς ἀμυγδάλοις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Diocl.fragment 126, compare 117; ἡ οὐκ ἐπιτηδείως τῷ σώματι διδομένη τροφὴ οὐ τρέφει 2nd c.AD: Soranus Medicus 1.49; πυρῶν.. ὅσοι κοῦφοι.. ἧττον τρέφουσι 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus “Vict.Att” 6; τὸ δέρμα πᾶν αὐτοῖς ὡς ἂν ὑπὸ φλεγματώδους αἵματος τρεφόμενον οἰδαλέον γίνεται [prev. author] 18(2).118, compare 106. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> <b>bring up, rear, educate,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Fragmenta” 19, 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 3.53, etc.; τῷ λόγῳ τ. καὶ παιδεύεις 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 534d; θρέψαι καὶ παιδεῦσαι 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 59.18; Δήμητερ ἡ θρέψασα τὴν ἐμὴν φρένα 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 479 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἡ θρέψασα (i.e. γῆ) the <b>motherland,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Lycurgus Orator 47 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>middle</i>, ἐθρέψω Ξέρξην ἐν τοῖς αὐτοῖς ἤθεσιν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 695e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἡ θρεψαμένη one's <b>motherland,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Lycurgus Orator 85:\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] —<i>passive</i>, ὀρθῶς, εὖ τραφῆναι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 401e, Alcaeus1.120e\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; παιδείᾳ, ἐν ταύτῃ τῇ παιδείᾳ τ., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Lg.” 695c, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Cynegeticus” 1.16; ἐν πολυτρόποις ξυμφοραῖς 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.44; ἐν φιλοσοφίᾳ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 172c; ἐν χλιδῇ 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 4.5.54; ἐν ἐλευθερίᾳ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 175d, “Mx.” 239a; ἐν ἄλλοις νόμοις 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1327a14; ἐν φωνῇ βαρβάρῳ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 341c; πάσαις Μούσαισι “BCH” 50.444 (Thespiae, 4th c.AD). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__V</b></Level2> the <i>passive</i> sometimes came to mean little more than <b>to be,</b> ἐπ᾽ ἐμοὶ πολέμιον ἐτράφη (i.e. τὸ γένος) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 335 (Lyric poetry), compare “Th.” 141, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 805. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level1><b>__B</b></Level1> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus uses an _intransitive_ \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>aorist 2</i> <i>active</i> ἔτραφον in <i>passive</i> sense (which is to τρέφομαι, τέτροφα (<i>intransitive</i>) as ἔδρακον to δέρκομαι, δέδορκα, etc.), ὃς.. ἔτραφ᾽ ἄριστος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 21.279; λέοντε ἐτραφέτην ὑπὸ μητρί 5.555 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τραφέμεν (<i>Epic dialect</i> for τραφεῖν)[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7.199, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.28, +others\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἐπεὶ τράφ᾽ ἐνὶ μεγάρῳ, i. e. when he <b>was well-grown,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.661 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—as <i>transitive</i> the <i>aorist 2</i> is used by [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus only in 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.90, and τράφε in 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 3.53 is _Doric dialect_ \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>imperfect</i>:—ἐτράφην is perhaps post-Homeric; <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>singular</i> τράφη is see reading in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.661, _1st pers._ _plural_ ἐτράφημεν and _1st pers._ _sing._ ἐτράφην \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] (περ) variants in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 23.84; τράφη is in all codices of 3.201, 11.222, which should probably be emended from 2.661 \">Refs</a>]; <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>plural</i> ἔτραφεν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 23.348 (variant{ἔτραφον}), 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.417 (variant{ἔτραφον})\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; τράφεν in all codices of [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.251, 266, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.201, also (with see l. τράφον) in 4.723 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: the <b>vox nihili</b> ἐτράφεμεν, found in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.84 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] as cited by [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 1.149, was emended by Scaliger to ἐτράφομεν\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]:—the <i>reduplicate</i> <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>singular</i> τέτραφ᾽ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 21.279 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>plural</i> τέτραφεν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 23.348 \">Refs</a>], are ff. <i>lines</i>, though found in many codices Later this <i>aorist</i> became obsolete, except in <i>Epic dialect</i> imitators, as in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Callimachus Epicus “Hymnus in Jovem” 55, 2nd-3rd c.AD: Oppianus Anazarbensis Epicus “Halieutica - Poetae Bucolici et Didactici” 1.774. \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5142","accentedUnicode":"τρέφω","shortDef":"to care for, feed, nurse; (<i>passive</i>) to be nurtured, cared for","mediumDef":"to care for, feed, nurse; (<i>passive</i>) to be nurtured, cared for <br /><b>to nourish; to feed, support, cherish, care for, provide for,</b>","stepGloss":"to feed","stepTransliteration":"trefō","count":9,"_es_Definition":"alimentar, proveer alimento ; nutrir, sostener, mantener ; amamantar ; criar (niños)","_zh_tw_Definition":"1) 滋養, 餵養<br>2) 照顧, 養育 (孩子) (路4:16)","_zh_Definition":"1) 滋养, 喂